WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.560
My name is Nick Tierney and I'm here to talk about the future of missing data.

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:14.760
So I fully hate missing data. It disrupts your data analysis because you need to stop

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:20.799
and work out how much is missing and think, why is it missing? Why?

00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:24.320
Missing data controls messages. I mean, imagine if what I said just then was bleeped out.

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:27.320
You might get a different idea of what I was saying.

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:32.919
I redacted hate and missing data. It redacted your data analysis because redacted and work

00:00:32.919 --> 00:00:39.720
out how redacted is missing and think, why redacted and redacted and redacted? Why?

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:44.560
But the truth is I actually love missing data in a funny way.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:48.040
Understanding it's hard, but it has an extra challenge, a little bit of spice to a data

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:52.480
analysis. And it's been something that I've found really exciting and curious about a

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:54.599
data analysis project.

00:00:54.599 --> 00:01:00.799
I've actually written two R packages to help explore your data and explore missing data.

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:05.360
And today I'm going to talk about two things, a principle of going from overview to relationship

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:09.599
to explore your missing data and a brief tour of missing data visualizations.

00:01:09.599 --> 00:01:14.120
Emphasis on the brief, I won't have time to explore them all in detail.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:18.120
So the first one I'd recommend is an overview, viz miss. This gives you a bird's eye view

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:24.440
of your missing data. Here the rows are your observations and the columns are your variables.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:29.519
If we look at the data here, we see that the black spots here are missing and the gray

00:01:29.519 --> 00:01:36.599
are present. And what we take away from this is that air temperature C is missing and humidity

00:01:36.599 --> 00:01:40.639
is also missing. They have two big chunks of missing data. There's also a few times

00:01:40.639 --> 00:01:46.639
where there's these black streaks and that indicates that some variables go missing together.

00:01:46.639 --> 00:01:51.680
We also know that there is extra information on the amount of missing in each variables.

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:56.360
Here's 11% missing in air temperature and 12% missing in humidity.

00:01:56.360 --> 00:01:59.639
So now we go from the overview here and we take these two variables that are interesting

00:01:59.639 --> 00:02:04.919
to us, that have a lot of missing, and we plot them together to explore a relationship.

00:02:04.919 --> 00:02:09.839
We can do this with ggplot, with air temperature on the x-axis and humidity on the y-axis,

00:02:09.839 --> 00:02:15.479
but we get a little interesting problem here, which says that it's removed 171 rows containing

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:21.119
missing values. So how do you show these values that are removed, how do you show missing

00:02:21.119 --> 00:02:28.399
values if they're missing? You can use geom.misspoint. This is a regular ggplot geom and this will

00:02:28.399 --> 00:02:34.960
impute the values of the data to be lower than the range of the data, so they're off

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:38.679
to the side here and in a different color. So let's break this down and look at each

00:02:38.679 --> 00:02:45.119
axis one at a time. The values in red on the x-axis are air temperature values, which are

00:02:45.119 --> 00:02:50.960
missing for humidity. We see that the distribution of these values here matches the first cluster

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:57.919
on the left, and on the y-axis are the humidity values that have missing air temperature values.

00:02:57.919 --> 00:03:01.199
Interesting again here is that this cluster value seems to match the second cluster on

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:05.479
the right of the present values here. So what we learn from this is that missingness is

00:03:05.479 --> 00:03:10.320
aligned with these two clusters of air temperature and humidity, and let's explore this further

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:15.960
by exploring this relationship with another variable, year. We can just use facetwrap

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:21.279
year, just like a regular ggplot geom, we then get two subplots here, and what we notice

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:30.279
is something very interesting, that we get these different values for, well, these distributions

00:03:30.279 --> 00:03:33.240
of missingness are shown for each of these different years, and we've learned something

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:39.240
really interesting, there's a different missing value pattern for each year. Now I'm going

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:45.639
to briefly explore some more missing data visualizations. So you can use gtmissvar to

00:03:45.639 --> 00:03:48.960
explore the missingness in each variable, and you can even show this instead of the

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:54.320
number to the percent, and you can even explore this with a facet. Hey look, we found it again,

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:59.419
the pattern of missing values for each year in our dataset. You can use gtmissupset to

00:03:59.419 --> 00:04:06.360
explore combinations of missingness in simple datasets, or more complex ones. You can even

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:11.399
use gtmissfactor to explore the percent of missingness of all variables grouped by another

00:04:11.399 --> 00:04:16.920
factor. Here we see the percent of missing data over all variables in this dataset, for

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:22.959
these different levels of marital status. With some help from the R Consortium, I'm

00:04:22.959 --> 00:04:27.239
really happy to say we'll be adding some more tools for visualizing missing data. I'll briefly

00:04:27.239 --> 00:04:32.000
talk about two new additions that I think will be really cool. Geomisshistogram will

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.640
show the amount of missing values alongside a univariate distribution by imputing it below

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:41.559
the range of the data. This gives us a general sense of the amount of missing values in the

00:04:41.559 --> 00:04:46.320
air temperature data here in this example. Geoimputedpoint will take in a dataset and

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:53.160
identify any imputed values and will also show the values that are missing. And in some

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:59.119
very exciting news, I would love to introduce a book that I'm working on with Alison Horst

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:05.279
called The Missing Book. It contains exercises on missing data and general workflows on exploring

00:05:05.279 --> 00:05:09.440
missing values and imputations, and the aim is to have a general book to guide you through

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:15.279
exploring your data with some case studies of real missing data.

00:05:15.279 --> 00:05:19.959
So I'll wrap up now by saying that the future of missing data is its presence. It's its

00:05:19.959 --> 00:05:26.959
presence in software, in your data analysis, in tutorials, in how we think about data generally.

00:05:26.959 --> 00:05:34.320
Funnily enough, missing data is almost always present, so let's make sure we don't forget it.

